  "prompt": "What are the hardest puzzles asked in interview?",
  "response": "Interview puzzles, especially those that are considered hard, often require lateral thinking, problem-solving skills, and creativity. Here are some examples of challenging interview puzzles that have been asked in various contexts, particularly in tech companies:\n\n1. **The Classic Light Bulb Problem**:\n   You have three light bulbs in a room and three switches outside the room. You can toggle the switches as many times as you want, but you can only enter the room once. How do you determine which switch controls which bulb?\n\n2. **The Two Eggs Problem**:\n   You are given two identical eggs and access to a 100-story building. The eggs may break when dropped from a certain floor and will not break if dropped from below that floor. What is the minimum number of drops required to find the highest floor from which an egg can be dropped without breaking?\n\n3. **The 100 Prisoners Problem**:\n   100 prisoners are lined up, each wearing a hat that is either black or white. Each prisoner can see everyone else's hat but not their own. Starting from the back of the",
